1) What is JavaScript, and what is its primary use?
JavaScript is a high-level, interpreted programming language used mainly to make web pages interactive and dynamic.

What it is

JavaScript is one of the core technologies of the web (along with HTML and CSS). It runs directly in the browser and can also run on servers using environments like Node.js.

Primary Use

Its main purpose is to add behavior and interactivity to websites.

2) What are the basic data types in JavaScript?
Primitive Data Types (built-in basics)

Number
Represents both integers and decimals.

let age = 20;
let price = 99.99;

String
Represents text (characters inside quotes).

let name = "Pashvitha";

Boolean
Represents logical values: true or false.

let isLoggedIn = true;

Undefined
A variable declared but not assigned a value.

let x;

Null
Represents an intentional empty value.

let data = null;

BigInt
Used for very large integers beyond normal Number limits.

let big = 12345678901234567890n;

Symbol
Used to create unique identifiers (mostly for advanced use).

let id = Symbol("id");

3) How do you declare a variable in JavaScript?
Basic Syntax
keyword variableName = value;
a) Using let 
let age = 20;
Value can be changed later
b)  Using const (constant value)
const pi = 3.14;
Value cannot be reassigned
c) Using var 
var name = "Pashvitha";

4) What is the difference between null and undefined in JavaScript?

a) undefined
Means a variable is declared but not assigned
Automatically assigned by JavaScript
let x;
console.log(x); // undefined

b) null
Means intentional empty value
Assigned by the programmer
let y = null;